    <a title="Cheryl" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11255849-cheryl"><img alt="Cheryl" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1565547225p2/11255849.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1612593450?book_show_action=true">Apr 16, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cheryl" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cheryl" href="/user/show/11255849-cheryl">Cheryl</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780060594671" href="/book/show/9674087-crooked-letter-crooked-letter">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11255849-cheryl?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1612593450" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10603383807435822068"><i>Crooked Letter,</i> the crooked lives we live. Those crooked thoughts that alter trajectories, oh if only someone—a friend, a parent, a community, a town—could reach out and position a person&apos;s marred ways of thinking. Oftentimes, it doesn&apos;t happen this way, not if one lives in a crooked town. <br/><br/><b>Imagine</b> a life in ruins, simply because a person has been misunderstood. Imagine having a friend you could never publicly claim, a girlfriend you would always keep hidden, because of a small town&apos;s shortsighte</span>
  <span id="freeText10603383807435822068" style="display:none"><i>Crooked Letter,</i> the crooked lives we live. Those crooked thoughts that alter trajectories, oh if only someone—a friend, a parent, a community, a town—could reach out and position a person's marred ways of thinking. Oftentimes, it doesn't happen this way, not if one lives in a crooked town. <br /><br /><b>Imagine</b> a life in ruins, simply because a person has been misunderstood. Imagine having a friend you could never publicly claim, a girlfriend you would always keep hidden, because of a small town's shortsightedness. Imagine making one wrong turn and being blamed for an egregious incident. Imagine lives destroyed because of racism and sexism, those isms that still feed on parts of the small town life today.<br /><br /><b>Imagine</b> a life of forced solitude. <br /><i>
  <blockquote>Their lives had stopped, frozen, as if in a picture, and the days were nothing more than empty squares on a calendar.</blockquote>
</i> <br />There is only so much I can say about this novel without ruining it for you, for every word seems so intricately placed, every thought deftly illuminated, every story structure profoundly rendered. The mystery and pacing unfolds without obstruction. Structurally, this is one of those perfectly written books. <br /><i>
  <blockquote>When he left, Larry lay amid his machines, thinking of Silas, how time packs new years over the old ones but how those old years are still in there, like the earliest, tightest rings centering a tree, the most hidden, enclosed in darkness and shielded from weather. But then a saw screams in and the tree topples and the circles are stricken by the sun and the sap glistens and the stump is laid open for the world to see.</blockquote>
</i><br /><b>Imagine</b> painfully bearing other people's lies and secrets, yet being unaware you're doing so.<br /><br />Sure, the story takes place through interesting dialogue, a heartrending plot, and neatly developed characters, but to truly know Larry and Silas is to be engrossed within a nuanced tale of two Southern men who are very different, and yet quite similar, men shackled by similar heritage, shackled by more than they'd imagined. <br /><br /><b>Imagine</b> time distorted and bruised, time forgiven and healed.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10603383807435822068" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

